# INSTITUTIONAL STRUCTURE OF TRUST-BASED ORGANISATIONS v0.2
(Extension — Temporal Claim Structure)

Author: Kok Pian Gew  
Date: 2026  
Status: Conceptual Draft (v0.2)

---

## 19. TEMPORAL CLAIM STRUCTURE

### 19.1 PURPOSE

Traditional organisations are structured around a single dominant claim:

> **capital ownership**

This concentrates authority, reward, and control within one class.

This framework introduces:

> **a multi-layer temporal claim structure**

in which different forms of contribution are recognised across time,
with distinct rights, rewards, and roles.

---

## 19.2 CORE PRINCIPLE

> **Value within an institution arises from multiple temporal contributions, and no single claim class should dominate all dimensions of authority, reward, and control.**

---

## 19.3 FOUR TEMPORAL CLAIM CLASSES

The institution is structured across four primary temporal layers.

---

### 1. CONTRIBUTION TEMPORAL  
(Participation / Labour Layer)

Represents:

- time
- effort
- skill
- active participation

Characteristics:

- generates contribution signals
- directly produces economic value
- varies continuously with activity

Rights:

- share of labour-derived rewards
- influence through accumulated contribution signals

Constraint:

- inactive participants lose relative influence

---

### 2. CAPITAL TEMPORAL  
(Credit / Financing Layer)

Represents:

- financial capital
- credit provision
- risk-bearing capacity

Characteristics:

- enables project initiation and scaling
- does not directly produce output
- operates across time through risk exposure

Rights:

- return on capital
- priority claims within defined bounds

Constraint:

- returns are bounded by continuation requirements
- does not confer unlimited governance authority

---

### 3. INSTITUTIONAL TEMPORAL  
(Trust / Stewardship Layer)

Represents:

- governance structure
- institutional identity
- continuation responsibility
- protection of system integrity

Characteristics:

- non-extractive
- long-horizon
- responsible for maintaining boundaries and rules

Rights:

- authority to enforce constitutional constraints
- responsibility for continuation decisions

Constraint:

- cannot extract value beyond defined institutional margin
- must act within stated principles

---

### 4. INFORMATIONAL TEMPORAL  
(Signal / Platform Layer)

Represents:

- aggregated contribution signals
- system intelligence
- behavioural data derived from activity

Characteristics:

- accumulates over time
- improves system coordination and efficiency
- not equivalent to personal ownership

Rights:

- supports system optimisation
- informs decision-making and governance calibration

Constraint:

- must not override individual data rights
- operates only within defined privacy and usage boundaries

---

## 19.4 RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN CLAIM CLASSES

The four temporal classes interact but are not interchangeable.

Key rules:

- Contribution generates value  
- Capital enables value creation  
- Institution stabilises the system  
- Information improves coordination  

No class alone can sustain the system.

---

## 19.5 VALUE FLOW STRUCTURE

Economic value flows through the system as follows:

Contribution Temporal
→ generates output

Capital Temporal
→ enables scale and absorbs risk

Institutional Temporal
→ preserves system integrity and continuity

Informational Temporal
→ enhances efficiency and coordination

---

## 19.6 AUTHORITY DISTRIBUTION

Authority is distributed across layers:

- operational influence → contribution-based  
- financial claim → capital-based  
- boundary enforcement → institutional layer  
- system learning → informational layer  

No single layer controls all authority dimensions.

---

## 19.7 CONSTRAINTS ON DOMINANCE

To maintain stability:

- capital cannot dominate governance  
- contribution cannot override continuation constraints  
- institutional authority cannot become extractive  
- informational layer cannot become coercive  

---

## 19.8 TEMPORAL BALANCE CONDITION

The institution remains stable when:

- contribution is active  
- capital is sufficient but bounded  
- governance is consistent  
- information remains reliable  

Instability arises when any layer becomes:

- dominant
- disconnected
- misaligned

---

## 19.9 RELATIONSHIP TO EXISTING MODELS

Traditional shareholder model:

- single dominant claim (capital)

Mutual / cooperative models:

- partially distributed claims

This framework:

> **formalises multiple claim classes with distinct temporal roles**

---

## 19.10 INTERPRETATION

This structure is not a normative statement about fairness.

It is:

> **a structural model describing how institutional claims must be separated and balanced to sustain cooperation under continuation constraints.**

---

## 19.11 CORE FORMULATION

> **An institution operates as a multi-temporal claim system in which contribution, capital, governance, and information each represent distinct but interdependent sources of value, and stability requires that no single claim class dominates all dimensions of control and reward.**

---

## 19.12 STATUS

This extension is conceptual (v0.2).

Future work may include:

